NEW YORK -(Dow Jones)- The crumbling price of electricity in the western=20
U.S., attributed by many to federal price controls, has forced power plant=20
developers to cancel projects, calling into question whether there will be=20
enough electricity to meet demand in the Northwest this winter.=20
The cancellations of peaking plants and temporary, oil-fired generators -=20
high-cost units that provide power needed only when demand is highest - have=
=20
cut projected generating capacity in the Northwest by up to 1,000 megawatts,=
=20
about 3% of the combined peak demand of Washington, Oregon, Idaho and wester=
n=20
Montana.
"The price caps have added uncertainty," said Scott Simms, spokesman for=20
Enron Corp. (ENE) unit Portland General Electric Co. "If we look forward to=20
this winter and you see a diminished supply scenario, you can see why we hav=
e=20
concerns about regional reliability. That could put us in a position of=20
having rotating outages in the region."=20
About two weeks after the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission imposed limit=
s=20
on western power prices on June 19, Portland General halted installation of =
a=20
new 45-megawatt gas-fired peaking turbine at its existing Boardman power=20
plant.=20
The utility was developing the extra generation both to meet its customers'=20
needs and to sell some output to other Northwest utilities left short of=20
hydroelectric supplies due to this year's drought. A turbine that size could=
=20
power about 45,000 homes.=20
"You can directly attribute that to FERC price controls," Simms said.=20
After the FERC order, at least two utilities in Washington State ended=20
negotiations with NRG Energy (NRG) for supplies from new plants that NRG was=
=20
ready to build in time for winter. Both utilities - Tacoma Power and=20
Snohomish County Public Utility District - experienced significant supply=20
shortages in the past 12 months, paid very high prices in the spot market an=
d=20
had to raise customer electric rates by as much as 50%.=20
But both utilities told NRG, and later Dow Jones Newswires, that they had no=
=20
reason to sign long-term contracts to guarantee new supplies, because the=20
FERC had practically eliminated the financial risk of relying on the spot=20
market. NRG, as a result, scuttled plans to build peaking plants in=20
Washington that could have added 300 megawatts.=20
FERC's price controls, as well as supply-demand fundamentals, have=20
dramatically changed the economics of selling power into the West's open=20
market in the past few months.=20
The current western U.S. electricity price cap of $98 a megawatt-hour covers=
=20
the costs of generating power from easy-to-install but inefficient peaking=20
turbines, but not the capital costs of buying and installing new peakers. In=
=20
addition, the current price cap may soon be recalculated to a much lower=20
level. The cap is based largely on natural gas prices, which have been cut i=
n=20
half since the cap was first formulated in June.=20

