consumers are conserving electricity.=20
Jim Kemp, a senior executive for the Canadian utility TransAlta's (TA.TO)=20
merchant power group, TransAlta (TA.TO), for example, doesn't attribute the=20
cancellation of projects to price controls.=20
"I see it as due to demand-side control and new units," Kemp said. "The=20
market is sending out a signal that we have enough. Maybe this winter we wil=
l=20
find that we don't have enough, but that's not the signal the market is=20
sending now."=20
The spot market for power has been far below the federal price cap for two=20
months. Mild weather, a slowing economy and conservation efforts throughout=20
the West have made power from expensive peaking plants unnecessary except fo=
r=20
a few hours so far this summer.=20
"Prices started to come down before the FERC mitigation plan started," said=20
Tacoma Power supply analyst David Lucio, who was negotiating with NRG. "The=20
need to try to execute a contract wasn't as great with the prices falling."=20
Lucio said there should be enough capacity to get the Northwest through the=20
winter, barring abnormalities like a long, extended freeze.=20
Construction of dozens of peaking plants in the West is going forward in=20
cases where developers sold supply contracts in advance. TransAlta is=20
continuing construction of a 154-megawatt peaking plant in Washington,=20
because much of the plant's capacity was sold months ago.=20
"The number of announced projects is far and away more than what is needed=20
within the time frame we're talking about," said Dick Watson, a director wit=
h=20
the Northwest Power Planning Council.=20
Still, several western utilities have asked the FERC to raise the price cap.=
=20
Puget Sound Energy (PSD) told the FERC the cap "undercuts the Commission's=20
efforts to ensure adequate supplies of electricity."=20
